    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1987-05-27T14:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1987-05-27T14:00:00-05:00" n="26"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d26">
                <head>26. Minutes of a Domestic Policy Council Meeting<note n="1" type="source"
                        xml:id="d26fn1">Source: Reagan Library, Bledsoe, Ralph: Files, <gloss
                            target="#t_DPC_1">DPC</gloss> Meeting Minutes 1987–1988 (2). No
                        classification marking. The meeting took place in the Roosevelt Room at the
                        White House.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1987-05-27T14:00:00-05:00">May 27, 1987, 2 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="participants">
                    <head>PARTICIPANTS</head>
                    <item>Messrs. <persName corresp="#p_HDP_1">Hodel</persName>, <persName
                            corresp="#p_BOR_1">Bowen</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_HJS_1"
                            >Herrington</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_BWJ_1">Bennett</persName>,
                            <persName corresp="#p_MJC_1">Miller</persName>, <persName
                            corresp="#p_TCH_2">Thomas</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_WJC_1"
                            >Whitehead</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_TWHI_1">Taft</persName>,
                            <persName corresp="#p_BAI_1">Burns</persName>, Whitfield, Covitz,
                            <persName corresp="#p_CTK_1">Cribb</persName>, Bauer, Ms. <persName
                            corresp="#p_RNJ_1">Risque</persName>, Messrs. Culvahouse, Dawson,
                        Donatelli, Fitzwater, Griscom, Hobbs, Sprinkel, <persName corresp="#p_GGS_1"
                            >Green</persName>, Graham, Greenleaf, <persName corresp="#p_SRW_2"
                            >Sweet</persName>, Ms. <persName corresp="#p_HCE_1">Horner</persName>,
                        Messrs. <persName corresp="#p_KCE_1">Koop</persName>, Gould, Mason, Windom,
                        Galebach</item>
                </list>
                <p>[Omitted here is material unrelated to <gloss target="#t_AIDS_2"
                    >AIDS</gloss>.]</p>
                <p>The second issue was whether to do <gloss target="#t_HIV_1">HIV</gloss> testing
                    for immigrants and aliens. Mr. <persName corresp="#p_WJC_1">Whitehead</persName>
                    expressed State Department concerns that it is not so much the foreign policy
                    aspects of testing as the practical aspects, such as cost and the thought that
                    only a small number of people will be intercepted. He pointed out the
                    complications in doing a blood test in a foreign country since facilities are
                    not often suited to doing <gloss target="#t_HIV_1">HIV</gloss> tests. Mr. Bauer
                    pointed out that it wouldn’t take many immigrant <gloss target="#t_AIDS_2"
                        >AIDS</gloss> cases in which the Federal government picks up the cost, to
                    pay for a large number of <gloss target="#t_HIV_1">HIV</gloss> tests. Mr. Bauer
                    said the Justice Department favors testing of immigrants and aliens for <gloss
                        target="#t_HIV_1">HIV</gloss> and that he believed that the practical
                    problems could be worked out.</p>
                <pb facs="0120" n="74" xml:id="pg_74"/>
                <p>Secretary <persName corresp="#p_HJS_1">Herrington</persName> said that we already
                    test for tuberculosis and venereal diseases, and adding <gloss target="#t_HIV_1"
                        >HIV</gloss> would be appropriate. Mr. Bauer reiterated support for adding
                        <gloss target="#t_HIV_1">HIV</gloss> to the list of dangerous diseases
                    because of the cost of health care for immigrants to this country who have
                        <gloss target="#t_HIV_1">HIV</gloss>. Mr. <persName corresp="#p_WJC_1"
                        >Whitehead</persName> questioned whether the money for testing immigrants
                    and aliens would be well spent. He had no problem with identifying clinical
                        <gloss target="#t_AIDS_2">AIDS</gloss> on the list of contagious diseases
                    but continued to oppose the listing of <gloss target="#t_HIV_1">HIV</gloss>.
                    Secretary <persName corresp="#p_BWJ_1">Bennett</persName> said he believed it
                    was inconsistent to test domestically and not abroad. He stated support for the
                    listing of <gloss target="#t_HIV_1">HIV</gloss>.</p>
                <p>[Omitted here is material unrelated to <gloss target="#t_AIDS_2"
                    >AIDS</gloss>.]</p>
